ukaojescfktcisnkeoumsccszeeifipehkeqrgie length 5 63468 page 1761 Spanish politician Bárbara Dührkop (2014). Bárbara Dührkop Dührkop (born 27 July 1945, in Hanover) is a Spanish politician and member of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party (PSOE). She was until 2009 a Member of the European Parliament, where she was a vice-chair of the Socialist Group and sat on the European Parliament's Committee on Budgets, as well as being a substitute on the Committee on Agriculture and Rural Development and the Committee on Budgetary Control. Her husband Enrique Casas was assassinated by the Comandos Autónomos Anticapitalistas (CAA) in 1984.[1] Education[edit] 1971: Graduate in humanities of the University of Uppsala (Sweden) 1973: Language teacher in Hamburg Career[edit] 1974-1978: Lecturer at the University of Erlangen–Nuremberg 1978-1987: Language teacher at the Usandizaga Institute and the German School (San Sebastián) 1995: Chair of the Board of the German School in San Sebastian 1999: Member of the executive committee of the Socialist Party of Euskadi - Euskadiko Ezkerra since 1987: Member of the European Parliament 1989-1994: Socialist coordinator on the Committee on Culture and Education 1994-1999: Vice-chairwoman of the Committee on Budgets 1995: Awarded the Mujer Progresista prize Decorations[edit] Grand Cross of the Order of Civil Merit of the Republic of Austria See also[edit] 2004 European Parliament election in Spain References[edit] ^ Luis R. Aizpeolea. «15 tiros y 25 años después». El País. External links[edit] Personal profile of Bárbara Dührkop Dührkop in the European Parliament's database of members Declaration (PDF) of financial interests (in Spanish) This article about a Member of the European Parliament from Spain is a stub. You can help Wikipedia by expanding it. v t e contentType 24 text/html; charset=UTF-8 url 59 https://en.wikipedia.org:443/wiki/B%C3%A1rbara_D%C3%BChrkop responseCode 3 200 